4sight signal analysis¶

Summary¶

Signal predictive power¶

Suggested actions:¶

Keep invest

  • Ask what time can the signal for day t be send
  • Ask the vendor for 2020 data to backtest again the simple strategy I designed
  • If convincing, pursue the analysis as the signal shows strong predictive features
  • Live trading with paper money for a month

Observations:¶

After this premilinary analysis, the signal shows strong predictive power. Indeed, a very basic trading strategy designed analysis pre 2018 data was able to generate strong performance.
The analysis pre 2018 indicates statistical significance of the relashionship between the signal and the adjusted close daily moves. See below the trading strategy performance in 2019(similar results were obtained before that) and the signal feature S formula below:

Buy and Hold Long the ETF when S>1%, Short when S<-1%
# Trading days 276 276
Trading period from 11/20/2018 to 12/26/2019 from 11/20/2018 to 12/26/2019
Daily acount size \$100 \$100
Total PnL \$15 \$38
Annualized Return 12% 39%
Annual Standard Deviation 17% 17%
Sharpe Ratio 0.75 2.46
Proportion of days traded 100% 77%
Proportion of positive days 54% 59%
Maximum drawdown 25% 35%

where $S_t = Log Return ( Signal_{t-3} + Signal_{t-6} )$
we pay 1 basis point of transaction cost per buy/sell order.

Data issues¶

Suggested actions:¶

  • Notice the vendor of the Signal data issues and ask for root causes?: storage system or generating system?
  • Negociate with the vendor about a course of action, compensation/penalty if their system fail to send a signal before a define hour of the day or send an absurd value

Observations:¶

Note that at the end of each issue we take the action specified in brackets

  • General
    • Calendar is matching NYSE calendar
    • Data on off-market days? (Deleted)
      • labor day: July 4th 2017
      • 2 weekends in 2018: May 19th/20th and June 23rd/24th
    • Missing 1 week of data: November 12th to 16th 2018 (Ignored)
  • Signal
    • No values in 2020 (Deleted)
    • 5 incorrect high values: July 13th 2016, March 22nd 2019, November 13th 2017, October 9th 2018 (Fill Forward)
  • Close, Adjusted close
    • 4 days where the ratio Adj Close/Close is not respected(Corrected)
    • 2 weeks where the open and close prices are constant and inputed: September 11th to 22nd 2017 (Deleted)
  • High, Low
    • 2 days Low>High(Corrected)
    • 8 days close or open price were out of the bounds. (Corrected)

# Create a calendar

early = nyse.schedule(start_date=dstr(df.index.min()), end_date=dstr(df.index.max()))
mkt_dt = mcal.date_range(early, frequency='1D').strftime("%Y-%m-%d")

data_dt = df.index.strftime("%Y-%m-%d")

# We use the reference time series to correct the series error values

def fixClose(series, ref, max_move = 20):
    abs_moves = (df[series].diff(periods=1)[1:]).abs()
    # for one anomaly we observe two consecutives abnormal moves. The anomaly is at the first date
    anom_dates = abs_moves[abs_moves>=max_move].index   
    
    df.loc[anom_dates[::2],series] = df.loc[anom_dates[::2],ref] * np.array(df.loc[anom_dates[1::2],series]/df.loc[anom_dates[1::2],ref])
    print(anom_dates[::2])

In the graph we clearly observe a lag between the signal and the adjusted close prices.

In [324]:
maxlag = 6
signalNames = ['Signal']
for lag in range(1,maxlag+1):
    signalNames.append('Signal.L%d'%lag)
    df['Signal.L%d'%lag] = df['Signal'].shift(lag)

In order to make the series first order stationary we consider the log-return. Given stationary times series we are able to identify correlations and causal relationships.

In [325]:
def bivMove(start,end):
    return end - start
def univMove(x):
    return bivMove(x.shift(),x.shift())

def bivReturn(start,end,loga = True):
    if loga:
        return bivMove(np.log(start), np.log(end))
    else:
        return bivMove(start, end)/start
def univReturn(x,loga = True):
    return bivReturn(x.shift(),x,loga)


def bivVol(start,end):
    return np.square(bivReturn(start, end,False))
def univVol(x):
    return np.square(bivReturn(x.shift(), x,False))

Feature engineering. For this preliminary analysis we only focus on Adjusted Close daily log returns

2.2 Correlation between the signal and the Adjusted Close price¶

In the training set(2015-2017) we find significant correlation between the Adjusted close price log return(Y) and the lag 3(X3) and 6(X6) Signal log returns.

Trading Y based on X3 gives good results.

Since the signal shows MA(1) autocorrelation scheme, we assume that X3 and X6 could contains independent information about Y and we simply sum them to build a signal feature to trade.

Observation from the end of the analysis: it would be more relevant to split the price return into 3 groups (high positive, low, high negative) and measure the signal classification power.

def shortName(name):
    short_dict = {'Signal':'S','LogReturn':'','Adj ':'a','Open':'O','Close':'C','LowHigh':'HL'}
    for sub in short_dict.keys():
        name = name.replace(sub, short_dict[sub])
    return name
data_print = data[var_names].copy()
data_print.columns = data_print.columns.to_series().apply(shortName)

The 3 and 6 lags are uncorrelated so we build a stronger signal by summing them.

# lags = [3,6]

# weights = [1,2,1]
def generateFeature(mdata,lags = [3,6],weights=None):
    if not weights:
        weights = np.ones(len(lags))
    snames = ['Signal.L%s'%lag for lag in lags if lag!=0]
    if 0 in lags:
        snames = 'Signal' + snames

    mdata['SignalFeature'] = np.array(mdata[snames]) @ np.array(weights)/ np.sum(weights)
    mdata['SignalFeatureLogReturn'] = univReturn(mdata['SignalFeature'])
    return mdata
data = generateFeature(data)
data_train = generateFeature(data_train)

date_str = lambda x: x.strftime('%m/%d/%Y')

def pnlSimple(mdata,amount,returnName,signalName,thld_buy=-100,thld_sell=-100,plot_dist = False,trading_cost=1):
    
    c = trading_cost/10000 #trading cost is in bps. c is the trading cost per 1 dollar of order.
    output = list()
    hold = False
    if thld_buy==-100 and thld_sell==-100:
        hold = True
    
    if hold:
        output.append('Buy and Hold')
    else:
        output.append('Long the ETF when S>%d%%, Short when S<%d%%'%(100*thld_buy,100*thld_sell))
    sign = - 1*(mdata[signalName]<thld_sell) + 1*(mdata[signalName]>thld_buy) 
    
    if(plot_dist):
        title = 'Returns distribution from %s to %s'%(date_str(mdata.index[0]),date_str(mdata.index[-1]))
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
        sns.histplot(data=mdata[sign==1], x=yrname, color="skyblue", label="Positive signal", kde=True)
        if(hold):
            fig.legend(labels=['Buy days'])
        else:
            sns.histplot(data=mdata[sign==-1], x=yrname, color="red", label="Negative signal", kde=True)
            sns.histplot(data=mdata[sign==0], x=yrname, color="grey", label="Mixed signal", kde=True).set_title(title)
            fig.legend(labels=['Buy days','Sell days','Flat Days'])

    r_hold = np.exp(mdata[returnName])-1
    r = r_hold * sign
    if hold:
        r[0]-=c
        r[r[r != 0].index[-1]] -=c
    else:
        r[r!=0] -= 2*c 

    output.append('%d trading days from %s to %s' %(mdata.shape[0],date_str(mdata.index[0]),date_str(mdata.index[-1])))
    output += lreturnStats(r,amount)
    return output

We invest the same amount every day and clear the portfolio between each day

In [352]:
def lreturnStats(r,amount):
    r_traded = r[r!=0]
    pnl = amount*np.sum(r)
    output = list()
    output.append('Daily acount size: %s'%locale.currency(amount))
    output.append('Total PnL: %s'%locale.currency(pnl))
    
    aer = 100*(np.prod(r+1)**(252/len(r)) - 1)
    output.append('Annualized Return: %d%%'%aer)
    std = 100*(r_traded.std() * np.sqrt(252))
    output.append('Annual Standard Deviation: %d%%'%std)
    sr = r_traded.mean()/r_traded.std() * np.sqrt(252)
    output.append('Sharpe Ratio: %.2f'%sr)
    ppd = 100*len(r_traded)/len(r)
    output.append('Proportion of days traded: %d%%'%ppd)
    ppm = 100*np.mean(r_traded>0)
    output.append('Proportion of positive days: %d%%'%ppm)
    
    s=(r+1).cumprod()
    dd = 100*np.ptp(s)/s.max()
    output.append('Maximum drawdown: %d%%'%dd)
    return output

3.2 Define stable trading strategy (before 2017 VS 2018)¶

We keep the +/- 1\% thresholds to buy/sell the etf since they reach the best performance while being stable accross time

  • Low signal threshold (0) allows us to trade every day while outperforming the buy and hold strategy in every period
  • High signal threshold (1%) select provides an improved performance consistant across both period.
  • Very high signal threshold (>1%) does not select enough trades and lead to very variable performance
